# 7. Component Rules

Each reusable component should include:

* Loading state
* Empty state
* Error state
* Responsive layout
* Accessibility labels
* Keyboard support

---

# 8. Git Workflow

Branch Naming

feature/<feature-name>

bugfix/<issue-name>

hotfix/<issue-name>

Commit Format

feat:

fix:

refactor:

docs:

test:

chore:

Example

feat: add citizen question submission wizard

---

# 9. Environment Variables

Never hardcode:

* API URLs
* Database URLs
* Secrets
* Tokens
* Keys

Always use environment variables.

---

# 10. Error Handling

Frontend

* Friendly error messages
* Retry options where appropriate

Backend

* Standard API response envelope
* Log errors with Request ID
* Never expose internal stack traces

---

# 11. Logging

Log

* API requests
* AI jobs
* Authentication
* Report generation
* Email delivery

Do not log:

* Passwords
* Secrets
* JWT tokens
* API keys

---

# 12. Security Standards

* HTTPS only
* JWT for protected APIs
* RBAC authorization
* Input validation
* ORM only (no raw SQL unless justified)
* Soft delete for citizen data
* Audit logging for admin actions

---

# 13. Performance Standards

Frontend

* Lighthouse ≥95
* Lazy loading
* Code splitting
* Image optimization

Backend

* Async endpoints where appropriate
* Database indexing
* Redis caching
* Background jobs for long-running tasks

---

# 14. Testing Standards

Frontend

* Component tests
* Accessibility checks

Backend

* Unit tests
* API tests
* Integration tests

End-to-End

* Citizen submission
* AI processing
* Report generation
* Email scheduling

---

# 15. Documentation Rules

Every new feature must include:

* Updated API documentation
* Database migration (if required)
* README updates (if applicable)
* Inline comments only where necessary

---

# 16. AI Development Rules

AI assistants must:

* Read all project documents before coding.
* Never invent features not present in the documentation.
* Never modify architecture without approval.
* Reuse existing components before creating new ones.
* Generate production-ready, typed, maintainable code.
* Follow existing folder structure.
* Respect design tokens and UI system.
* Keep commits focused on one feature at a time.

---

# 17. Definition of Done

A task is complete only when:

* Feature implemented
* Tests passing
* Responsive
* Accessible
* Secure
* No lint errors
* No type errors
* Documentation updated
* Code reviewed

